```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** A nav logo, wordmark, or site identity line wraps to two lines or gets compressed when the viewport narrows.

**Why it's wrong:** Logo and navigation identity lines represent the site's core identity. A two-line "Yilan Gao" or a compressed wordmark signals a broken layout — it is never acceptable at any viewport width, even narrow desktop. These elements are not content; they are structural identity. Yielding them to viewport pressure is a category error.

**Identity Priority Hierarchy**

All nav-bar elements must be classified before implementation:

| Priority | Class | Rule | Example elements |
|----------|-------|------|-----------------|
| **1 — Immovable** | Logo, wordmark, site name | Never wraps, never shrinks, never moves to a second line, at any viewport width | "Yilan Gao" logo link, logoMark icon |
| **2 — Yield** | Descriptive / contextual content | MAY wrap to 2 lines; absorbs ALL pressure from Priority 1 items | Tagline ("Designer, AI systems experience…"), nav links |

Priority 2 elements exist to absorb overflow pressure so Priority 1 elements never have to. If a Priority 2 element cannot fit, it wraps. If it cannot wrap, it clips. It never pushes the logo.

**Three-layer defense required for Priority 1 elements:**

```css
/* Layer 1: row-level — prevent the flex row from ever wrapping */
.navInner {
  flex-wrap: nowrap;
}

/* Layer 2: item-level — prevent compression and floor the box size */
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;
  min-width: max-content; /* closes the gap between "won't compress" and "won't shrink below content" */
}

/* Layer 3: text-level — prevent internal text from wrapping */
.logoText {
  white-space: nowrap;
}

/* Yield side: absorb all excess pressure */
.links {
  min-width: 0;
  overflow: hidden; /* prevents reverse-propagation of pressure to the logo */
}
```

All three layers must be present simultaneously. Any single layer alone is insufficient:
- `flex-shrink: 0` alone → flex row may still wrap the item to line 2
- `white-space: nowrap` alone → item won't wrap internally but can still be compressed
- `flex-wrap: nowrap` on container alone → item can still be flex-compressed below its content size

**Correct alternative:** Apply all three layers to every Priority 1 nav element. Add `overflow: hidden` to every Priority 2 yield container. Annotate both with the Identity Priority Hierarchy classification in comments so future agents understand why the rules exist.

**See:** FB-146 (nav logo "Yilan Gao" wrapping to two lines under squeeze)
```

